ional 'politics of survival' these women seek to subvert the dominant narratives of 'crisis' and 'activism'.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aMinority womenxSocial conditionszFrance. 0aMinority womenxSocial conditionszGreat Britain. 0aWomen political activistszFrance. 0aWomen political activistszGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aCollins, Patricia Hill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmejulu, Akwugo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311119663340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447327165zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447327165/original  a978-3-11-119663-3 Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA